# LiVEiT® SVG Standards

Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG) are the preferred format for official LiVEiT® logos, icons and graphical assets.

SVG files provide resolution-independent graphics that remain sharp across all screen sizes and display densities while maintaining small file sizes.

This document defines the standards for creating and using SVG assets within the LiVEiT® Framework.

---

# Why SVG

SVG is the preferred graphic format because it offers:

* Infinite scalability
* Small file sizes
* Crisp rendering on high-resolution displays
* Transparency support
* Easy integration with websites and applications
* Excellent browser compatibility

Whenever practical, SVG should be used instead of raster image formats.

---

# Official Assets

Only official SVG files supplied by the LiVEiT® project should be used for branding.

Official assets must not be:

* Redrawn
* Recreated
* Modified
* Simplified
* Traced from screenshots

If a required variation does not exist, request a new official asset rather than creating one manually.

---

# ViewBox

Every SVG should include a correctly defined `viewBox`.

Using a `viewBox` ensures that graphics scale correctly without distortion.

Width and height values should remain proportional to the original artwork.

---

# Responsive Scaling

SVG graphics should scale naturally within responsive layouts.

Avoid fixed dimensions where responsive behaviour is required.

Use CSS or application layout controls to determine displayed size while preserving the original aspect ratio.

---

# Optimisation

SVG files should be optimised before publication.

Optimisation should:

* Remove unnecessary metadata.
* Eliminate unused elements.
* Preserve visual accuracy.
* Maintain accessibility where applicable.

Optimisation must never alter the appearance of the artwork.

---

# Accessibility

Decorative SVG graphics should be hidden from assistive technologies where appropriate.

Meaningful graphics should include descriptive titles or alternative text when supported by the platform.

Logos used as navigation elements should always provide an accessible label.

---

# Colour Integrity

Official SVG assets must retain the approved LiVEiT® colour palette.

Do not:

* Replace colours.
* Add gradients that are not part of the official artwork.
* Change opacity.
* Apply filters.
* Add shadows or glow effects.

Consistency is essential for maintaining brand recognition.

---

# Naming Convention

SVG files should use clear, descriptive filenames.

Examples:

```text
liveit-logo-primary.svg
liveit-logo-white.svg
liveit-logo-black.svg
liveit-icon.svg
liveit-circle-aqua.svg
```

Use lowercase letters and hyphens for readability and consistency.

---

# File Structure

Official SVG assets should remain organised within the repository.

Example structure:

```text
branding/
└── assets/
    └── svg/
        ├── liveit-logo-primary.svg
        ├── liveit-logo-white.svg
        ├── liveit-logo-black.svg
        ├── liveit-icon.svg
        └── liveit-circle-aqua.svg
```

A consistent structure simplifies maintenance and version control.

---

# Version Control

SVG assets should be updated only when an official design revision has been approved.

When replacing an asset:

* Preserve the filename whenever possible.
* Document significant visual changes.
* Ensure compatibility with existing documentation and applications.

---

# Best Practice

When using SVG assets:

* Preserve the original proportions.
* Use official files only.
* Scale proportionally.
* Maintain transparency.
* Test rendering across multiple browsers and devices.

Following these standards ensures that the LiVEiT® visual identity remains consistent across all digital platforms.
